3.0 of 5 bubbles
A Must See That's in Fast Decline
Aug 2012 ‚Ä¢ Solo
Needless to see, Halong Bay is a must see if you are in Vietnam, and for good reason. It's one of the natural wonders of the world, and before commercialism hit it so hard Halong Bay must have been strikingly beautiful. However, the Vietnamese do not seem to be too concerned with preservation and are clearly trying to squeeze every penny possible out of this amazing place.

My expectations were incredibly high when I booked my 2 day, 1 night tour from Hanoi for $60 for a mid-level junk (took some negotiation, my roommate paid $90, so make sure to negotiate!). When I got to the bay, there was a sea of tourists. My group of about 15 people were herded on a junk and taken out to the main part of Halong Bay, about an hour away. Again, all you see is a sea of other junks and boats. The water was extremely dirty, floating plastic not uncommon. We visited the cave, which again was wall to wall tourists. Yes, the limestones are impressive, but just a little less impressive than if they were not completely surrounded by boats of all sizes. If you've been to other parts of SE Asia with similar natural landscapes (Krabi for example), Halong Bay is not as impressive as conveyed in pictures. Nonetheless, it's still definitely worth a visit (but a 2 day, 1 night tour is plenty)!
Written August 21, 2012
MaryT844
London, UK2 contributions
Aclass Opera cruise
Oct 2011 ‚Ä¢ Friends
I didn't plan to visit Halong Bay at first, due to some negative comments that I have read here and elsewhere but it turned out to be a pleasant surprise. My friends and I went for a 2-day-1-night tour with Aclass Opera Cruise. I was told the business was set-up last year, everything looked new and seemed to be in excellent condition. The staff was friendly and resourceful. Reasonable price, good food, a nice range of activities were covered. And I thought the scenery was awesome, especially if the weather was on your side.
