Huong Hai Junk cruise with overnight stay was absolutely wonderful
Apr 2011
My husband and I went on a Halong Bay tour with an overnight stay on board a Huong Hai junk. The boat was small with only 6 cabins with ensuites which gave it a lovely personal touch. Our Vietnamese guide named Man went out of his way to ensure our trip was enjoyable. The food was delightful, all fresh seafood and the boat had a lovely dining room with windows all around to enjoy the view. The open top deck had lounges for each guest and we lay there mesmerised and watched the sun set as our little boat sailed ever so quietly past the mountains, so very beautiful and tranquil. We were taken on a cave tour and fish farm tour in the bay. It was incredible value for low cost.
Written May 10, 2011
Smeets P
London, UK9,403 contributions
Just Amazing
I took this deluxe cruise as the Huong Hai junk has single cabin, which costs less for solo traveller and also I liked the itinerary.
The itinerary included visit to Sung Son cave, which was magnificient, Trek to Titov mountain had panoramic views of the Bay.
The junk was really nice and while we (11 people in my junk) were waiting in the harbour, I noticed that a small boat came to collect the rubbish from Huong Hai junk. This pleased me a lot as I had heard that the junks emptied their rubbish into the sea.
My single cabin was lovely, but my friends double room was bigger and looked better. The tour guide was Hai and he was wonderful. As soon as he knew I was vegetarian he made sure I had plenty of food.
We had about 8 courses at each mealtime and I was impressed. All the staff on the junk were fantastic.
Ha long bay is very beautiful and I loved every moment of my time there. I got up early to watch the sunrise and also saw the eagles.
We visited the luon cove in a small boat and fed the monkeys.
All the people on my group were really nice and we even exchanged emails.
I cannot say enough praises for my tour guide Hai, as he really looked after all of us and had good sense of humour.
I had most amazing time at Ha Long bay and will definitely return there. See the pictures of the junk, cabin, dining area for Houng hai junk and panoramic views from mountain.
Written December 6, 2010
CatOng-er
Sydney, Australia132 contributions
4.0 of 5 bubbles
calm after confusion
I'm writing this review because we had such an AWFUL time organising the tour, but were lucky we ended up with such an AMAZING time in halong bay itself.
My friend and I organised a 3 day 2 night Halong Bay tour from Hanoi, in the last week of september. We thought it would be easier doing it in hanoi, cos everyone said it was more expensive on the net.
But it wasn't really easier!
Maybe we did it wrong, because we spent one whole day in noisy honking dusty hot humid sweaty hanoi old quarter, getting semi-lost in the little streets, traipsing from one tour agency to the next, comparing tours. we were quite stressed, and they all sounded similar, but some were really expensive. we almost didn't want to go to halong bay after that!!!
we didn't realise there are like 5000 boat/tour operators in hanoi selling tours to halong bay - it was confusing trying to distinguish the real-deal operators from the copy-cats. we didn't even find some of the tour operators which were on our short-list (gleaned from extensive research via google and tripadvisor and lonely planet).
in the end, we went for Ocean Tours on 22 Hang Bac (just so you don't confuse it with a fake ocean tours). It was mid-range, approx US$130 for a 3day 2night tour. but we had extra night stay on the island, so extra $30.
AND BOY WERE WE GLAD WE DID!!!!
we had SUCH a great time in halong bay - it was so relaxing and beautiful, and we met some really nice people (which I also know was luck of the draw). even the haziness of the weather did not detract from the beauty
there are a few other tour companies around that street too, so you could start looking there.
the basic gist of most tours seemed pretty identical:
Day 1:
leave halong city noon-ish
sail
visit floating village
kayak around limestone things
stay on board boat one night
Day 2:
swim
visit caves (a bit like jenolan caves)
go to island
kayak / swim / trek on island
stay on island
Day 3:
sail back to Halong City
The things we liked about our tour / boat:
(1) small-ish boat, max 12-14 people
(2) all meals were on the boat (or island) - many operators pick you up from hanoi, but you have to have lunch in some restaurant in halong city before boarding boat (the city sounds overbuilt and touristy and yucky). we did not want to spend any time in halong city, after reading what we read in tripadvisor and lonely planet
(3) mid-range price
(4) kayaked around limestone karsts, and THROUGH them, and into this BEAUTIFUL cove that you can't get to any other way - it was amazing, feeling so close to nature
(5) the island stay was EXCELLENT. most tours go to Cat Ba island (the biggest island in halong bay, and it is really built up - like neon lights and discos and karaoke. good if you want some night life. Ocean Tours has its OWN little island opposite Cat Ba (it's called Cat Ong island, but no-one seemed to know its name..), and as i said there is only one "resort" on the island. and there are kayaks you can borrow anytime to kayak round the island, stopping at any of the 2-3 tiny beaches they have. (including amazing sunset from sunset beach). (beware the dogs on the island though - not very well-trained and may bite if over-excited while retrieving thrown sticks/rocks/etc)
(6) option to stay on island one more night - that was REALLY relaxing!
Initially we thought it would be a hassle to unpack off the boat to go onto any island and we might prefer to stay on a boat for 2 nights. But there is a catch - cos you don't sleep on the island, you have to sail back to Halong City to get customs paperwork done - sounded like a pain. so we're glad we went to the island, and even got one more day there to just relax.
otherwise, the time on the island is really short, just an afternoon and night, and leave after breakfast.
(7) our guide was great - really friendly, great command of english, funny guy, but not in-your-face
Things that may be an issue (but weren't really cos we were too relaxed to mind):
(1) not enough fruit on boat meals - bring own fruit & snacks
(2) have to buy water & other drinks on board (although meals are included)
(3) standard clean cabins, but not luxurious like some other junk boats (eg ginger junk). some of the deckchairs were falling apart
(4) no shade on top deck
(5) only one place to eat on Cat Ong island, but menu range wasn't too bad
If you get confused / overwhelmed by the number of tour operators, just have your list of the things you want, so you can ask them direct questions. they're pretty good though - they'll show you photos of their tours etc, and not be offended when you say "thanks i'll think about it" and go next door to check out the next tour.
Written November 16, 2007
James M
Devizes, UK16 contributions
